<subSubSection pageId="11" pageNumber="248" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="11.[811,1457,407,1645]" box="[813,957,407,433]" pageId="11" pageNumber="248">DESCRIPTION</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="11.[811,1457,407,1645]" pageId="11" pageNumber="248">
Thirteen cranio-dental remains (upper and lower teeth, mandible) have been attributed to the cave lion. This material and its stratigraphical distribution within the locality suggest a minimum number of seven individuals.Teeth measurements reveal significant size variability (
<tableCitation box="[1141,1222,566,593]" captionStart="TABLE" captionStartId="11.[132,143,860,878]" captionText="TABLE 7. — Dental measurements of Panthera (Leo) spelaea (Goldfüss, 1810) from Fouvent-Saint-Andoche. Measurements in mm. Abbreviations: see text." pageId="11" pageNumber="248">Table 7</tableCitation>
). Many palaeontological, phylogenetic, and biogeographical works have focused on the cave lion (e.g., 
<bibRefCitation author="BURGER J. &amp; ROSENDAHL W. &amp; LOREILLE O. &amp; HEMMER H. &amp; ERIKSSON T. &amp; GOTHERSTROM A. &amp; HILLER J. &amp; COLLINS M. J. &amp; WESS T. &amp; ALT K. W." box="[1013,1211,630,656]" pageId="11" pageNumber="248" pagination="841 - 849" refId="ref23686" refString="BURGER J., ROSENDAHL W., LOREILLE O., HEMMER H., ERIKSSON T., GOTHERSTROM A., HILLER J., COLLINS M. J., WESS T. &amp; ALT K. W. 2004. - Molecular phylogeny of the extinct cave lion Panthera leo spelaea. Molecular Phylogenetics and Evolution 30: 841 - 849." type="journal article" year="2004">
Burger 
<emphasis box="[1095,1146,630,656]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="248">et al.</emphasis>
2004
</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="HEMMER H." box="[1222,1385,630,656]" pageId="11" pageNumber="248" pagination="201 - 208" refId="ref25957" refString="HEMMER H. 2011. - The story of the cave lion - Panthera leo spelaea (Goldfuss, 1810) - a review. Quaternaire Hors-Serie (4): 201 - 208." type="journal article" year="2011">Hemmer 2011</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="SABOL M." pageId="11" pageNumber="248" pagination="229 - 236" refId="ref27609" refString="SABOL M. 2011. - Masters of the lost world: a hypothetical look at the temporal and spatial distribution of lion-like felids. Quaternaire Hors-Serie (4): 229 - 236." type="journal article" year="2011">Sabol 2011</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="STUART A. J. &amp; LISTER A. M." box="[879,1099,662,688]" pageId="11" pageNumber="248" pagination="2329 - 2340" refId="ref27858" refString="STUART A. J. &amp; LISTER A. M. 2011. - Extinction chronology of the cave lion Panthera spelaea. Quaternary Science Reviews 30: 2329 - 2340." type="journal article" year="2011">Stuart &amp; Lister 2011</bibRefCitation>
). In Europe, Late Pleistocene lions are both represented by the subspecies 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Goldfuss" baseAuthorityYear="1810" box="[1224,1455,693,720]" class="Mammalia" family="Felidae" genus="Panthera" kingdom="Animalia" order="Carnivora" pageId="11" pageNumber="248" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="spelaea" subGenus="Leo">
<emphasis box="[1224,1316,693,719]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="248">Panthera</emphasis>
(
<emphasis box="[1333,1369,694,719]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="248">Leo</emphasis>
) 
<emphasis box="[1384,1455,693,719]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="248">spelaea</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
described at Gailenreuth (OIS3, 
<collectingCountry box="[1166,1272,726,752]" name="Germany" pageId="11" pageNumber="248">Germany</collectingCountry>
), and the smaller form, 
<taxonomicName authority="(Filhol, 1891) (Filhol &amp; Filhol 1871)" authorityName="Filhol &amp; Filhol" authorityYear="1871" baseAuthorityName="Filhol" baseAuthorityYear="1891" class="Mammalia" family="Felidae" genus="Panthera" kingdom="Animalia" order="Carnivora" pageId="11" pageNumber="248" phylum="Chordata" rank="variety" species="spelaea" subGenus="Leo" variety="cloueti">
<emphasis box="[876,898,758,783]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="248">P.</emphasis>
(
<emphasis box="[907,942,758,783]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="248">Leo</emphasis>
) 
<emphasis box="[956,1025,757,783]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="248">spelaea</emphasis>
var. 
<emphasis box="[1071,1136,757,783]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="248">cloueti</emphasis>
(Filhol, 1891) (
<bibRefCitation author="FILHOL E. &amp; FILHOL H." pageId="11" pageNumber="248" refId="ref25244" refString="FILHOL E. &amp; FILHOL H. 1871. - Description des ossements de Felis spelaea decouverts dans la caverne de l'Herm (Ariege). Ed. Masson, Paris, 120 p." type="book" year="1871">Filhol &amp; Filhol 1871</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
of Jaurens (
<bibRefCitation author="BALLESIO R." box="[1006,1154,789,815]" pageId="11" pageNumber="248" pagination="61 - 102" refId="ref22726" refString="BALLESIO R. 1980. - Le gisement pleistocene superieur de la grotte de Jaurens a Nespouls, Correze, France. Les Carnivores (Mammalia, Carnivora). II. Felidae. Nouvelles Archives du Museum d'Histoire naturelle de Lyon 18: 61 - 102." type="journal article" year="1980">Ballesio 1980</bibRefCitation>
) (OIS3, 
<collectingCountry box="[1252,1329,790,816]" name="France" pageId="11" pageNumber="248">France</collectingCountry>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="11.[811,1457,407,1645]" pageId="11" pageNumber="248">
The taxonomic status of the small morph is a matter of debate, given that such size discrepancy may either reflect ecomorphotypy or sexual dimorphism. At Fouvent, the ratio B/L of the P4 and the m1 compared with fossil and living populations leads to some comments on the size of the different clines (
<figureCitation box="[929,994,980,1007]" captionStart="FIG" captionStartId="12.[135,146,1240,1258]" captionTargetBox="[132,1456,217,1203]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="FIG. 6. — Cave lion P. (leo) spelaea upper (P4) and lower (M1) carnassial Breadth and Length ratio compared to extant and extinct populations. Measurements in mm. The male and female lions areas figure the maximum range obtained for each variables (breadth and length)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4535137" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4535137/files/figure.png" pageId="11" pageNumber="248">Fig. 6</figureCitation>
). Thus, on the base of the m1 of Jaurens, a clear distinction appears between large-sized lions (Jaurens 
<emphasis box="[1432,1454,1013,1038]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="248">in</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="BALLESIO R." box="[813,959,1044,1070]" pageId="11" pageNumber="248" pagination="61 - 102" refId="ref22726" refString="BALLESIO R. 1980. - Le gisement pleistocene superieur de la grotte de Jaurens a Nespouls, Correze, France. Les Carnivores (Mammalia, Carnivora). II. Felidae. Nouvelles Archives du Museum d'Histoire naturelle de Lyon 18: 61 - 102." type="journal article" year="1980">Ballesio 1980</bibRefCitation>
) and a smaller form (Jaurens 
<emphasis box="[1274,1296,1045,1070]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="248">in</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="BALLESIO R." box="[1303,1451,1044,1070]" pageId="11" pageNumber="248" pagination="61 - 102" refId="ref22726" refString="BALLESIO R. 1980. - Le gisement pleistocene superieur de la grotte de Jaurens a Nespouls, Correze, France. Les Carnivores (Mammalia, Carnivora). II. Felidae. Nouvelles Archives du Museum d'Histoire naturelle de Lyon 18: 61 - 102." type="journal article" year="1980">Ballesio 1980</bibRefCitation>
; Espèche 
<emphasis box="[905,927,1077,1102]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="248">in</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="CLOT A. &amp; BROCHET G. &amp; CHALINE J. &amp; DESSE G. &amp; EVIN J. &amp; GRANIER J. &amp; MEIN P. &amp; CHAUVIRE C. &amp; OMNES J. &amp; RAGE J. C." box="[932,1099,1076,1102]" pageId="11" pageNumber="248" pagination="33 - 50" refId="ref23990" refString="CLOT A., BROCHET G., CHALINE J., DESSE G., EVIN J., GRANIER J., MEIN P., MOURER- CHAUVIRE C., OMNES J. &amp; RAGE J. C. 1984. - Faune de la grotte prehistorique du bois du Cantet (Espeche, Hautes-Pyrenees, France). Munibe 36: 33 - 50." type="journal article" year="1984">
Clot 
<emphasis box="[983,1033,1076,1102]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="248">et al.</emphasis>
1984
</bibRefCitation>
). In addition, many osteometrical datasets for Late Pleistocene cave lions confirm significant variability for the m1 (specimens smaller than 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Filhol &amp; Filhol" authorityYear="1871" baseAuthorityName="Filhol" baseAuthorityYear="1891" class="Mammalia" family="Felidae" genus="Panthera" kingdom="Animalia" order="Carnivora" pageId="11" pageNumber="248" phylum="Chordata" rank="variety" species="spelaea" variety="cloueti">
<emphasis box="[1315,1410,1140,1166]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="248">P. spelaea</emphasis>
var. 
<emphasis box="[813,877,1172,1198]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="248">cloueti</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and also larger than the biggest form of Jaurens).Moreover, current data confirm the presence of a strongly marked sexual dimorphism, increasing the probability of significant overlap between osteometrical dimensions. In our opinion, the different sizes observed at Jaurens seem to be more related to intraspecific sexual dimorphism than to any evolutionary stage or stratigraphical age-based discrepancy. Consequently, if we consider the small form of Jaurens as characteristic of females, the m1 of Fouvent which are very close in size could belong to females. The same thing is true concerning the two P4s of Fouvent, both presenting extreme values. The larger one could be associated to a large-sized male and the smaller to a female. However, it would be necessary to undertake a thorough revision of cave lion intraspecific variability in order to validate the concerned hypothesis.
</paragraph>
